http://purl.org/dc/elements/1.1/title.value: Computer Science and Mathematics Curriculum Framework

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: This course is designed to provide students with the opportunity to explore the uses of mathematics and computer programming as tools in creating effective solutions to complex problems. Students will develop and refine fundamental skills of computer science within a mathematical context. Computer Science and Mathematics may be counted as a fourth math credit course under Smart Core. Any reference to an algorithm or algorithms in this document includes both mathematics and computer science contexts. Throughout the course, students will use developmentally appropriate and accurate terminology when communicating about technology. Teachers are responsible for including the eight Standards for Mathematical Practice found in the Common Core State Standards for Mathematics (CCSS-M). Computer Science and Mathematics does not require Arkansas Department of Education approval.
Computational Thinking
Students will evaluate different data representations to solve problems.
Analyze the various mathematical bases

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., binary, decimal, hexadecimal) and convert between them

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Describe the relationship between binary and hexadecimal representations
Convert information between various encoding formats
Express the relationship between matrices and arrays
Compare techniques (e.g., sorting, statistics, searching) for analyzing massive data collections
Students will connect the development cycle of algorithm construction to problem solving.
Describe how mathematical and statistical functions, sets, and logic are used in computation
Utilize predefined mathematical functions and parameters to divide a complex problem into simpler parts, including parallel processing
Interpret truth tables from basic statements using Boolean operators (AND, OR, XOR, and NOT)
Explain ways in which sequence, selection, iteration, and recursion are building blocks of algorithms

Evaluate concepts of different types of functions, numerically and algebraically
  • quadratic functions, including the analysis of the discriminant and complex numbers
  • recursively defined functions, series, and sequences, including arithmetic and geometric
  • exponential and logarithmic functions (including inverse relationship between exponents and logarithms)
  • trigonometric functions to model physical situations (including right triangle trig, laws of sines and cosines)
  • scenarios involving velocity and other quantities that can be represented by vectors
Create systems of equations and matrices based on real-world situations
Solve systems of equations and matrices by finding inverses, determinants, and other methods
Analyze decisions and strategies using probability and statistical concepts
Students will create and evaluate algorithms to solve problems.
Utilize modeling and simulation techniques to represent and understand natural phenomena
Examine classical algorithms

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., discriminant in quadratic formula, matrix manipulation, searching, sorting, shortest path, minimum spanning tree

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Manipulate formulas and equations and apply them to algorithm development
Apply algorithm analysis and design techniques to solve problems
Write algorithms to solve mathematical problems using formulas, equations, matrices, and functions
Implement conditional statements that include if/then, if/then/else, case statements, and Boolean logic, in the design of algorithms
Represent algorithms using flowcharts and pseudocode
Combine standard function types using arithmetic operations
Analyze algorithms for correctness, clarity, and efficiency
Computing Practice and Programming
Students will evaluate the use of programming languages to solve problems and develop systems.
Compare and contrast computer programming languages and paradigms

http://purl.org/ASN/schema/core/comment.value: e.g., compiled and interpreted languages, procedural and object-oriented paradigms

http://purl.org/dc/terms/description.value: Diagram the program execution process
Determine the output of a given sample program without the use of a computer
Students will create, test, and use computer programs to solve problems.

Implement computing applications using the following software development tools and techniques
  • branching (if, if-else)
  • declare, define, and reference variables
  • lists/arrays
  • looping (for, while, do/while)
  • matrices/two-dimensional arrays
  • primitive data types
  • recursion
  • sequencing

Use various debugging and testing methods (e.g., debugging statements, breakpoints, memory inspection, test cases, unit testing, white box, black box, integration testing) to ensure program correctness
Cite evidence to support or refute the correctness of software solutions

Use the following Application Program Interfaces (API) and libraries to create problem solving computer programs
  • file input/output
  • math libraries (e.g., absolute value, square root, quadratic, exponentiation, trigonometry)
  • utilities (e.g., random number generators)

  • hacking
  • licensure
  • open source
